You said:
can i remove App.css and other things that created default
ChatGPT said:

Yes ‚Äî you can remove App.css and other default files created by Create React App (CRA) or Vite, as long as you adjust your imports accordingly. Here‚Äôs how to safely clean up a React project:
1. Remove default CSS

    Delete App.css and index.css (if you plan to write your own styles).

    Update App.js and index.js to remove import statements for those CSS files.

Example (App.js):

// Remove this line if you delete App.css
// import './App.css';

import Login from "./Login";

function App() {
  return (
    <div className="App">
      <Login />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;

2. Remove default images or logos

    Delete logo.svg if you aren‚Äôt using it.

    Remove any import of logo.svg in App.js.

3. Clean up index.js

    If you deleted index.css, remove:

// import './index.css';

    You can keep it minimal:

import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom/client";
import App from "./App";

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root"));
root.render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <App />
  </React.StrictMode>
);

4. Optional: Clean up public folder

    You can delete unnecessary files in public like favicon.ico, logo192.png, etc., or replace them with your own.

‚úÖ After this, your React project will be clean and only contain your components and styles, like the brown library login.

If you want, I can write a completely cleaned React project folder structure ready to paste in Ubuntu, with just the login page and necessary files. This way you can start immediately.

