Ah! That‚Äôs where the confusion is. You cannot remove index.js‚Äîthat is the main entry point React uses to render your app.

What you can safely remove are things like App.css, index.css, logo.svg, reportWebVitals.js, and any default imports you don‚Äôt use.

Here‚Äôs the correct minimal setup:
1. Keep src/index.js

import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom/client";
import App from "./App"; // Make sure App.js exists

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root"));
root.render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <App />
  </React.StrictMode>
);

    This file must exist. React uses it to find <div id="root"></div> in public/index.html and mount your app.

2. Keep public/index.html

Minimal version:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Library App</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div id="root"></div>
  </body>
</html>

3. Remove safely

    App.css ‚Üí remove import from App.js if deleted

    index.css ‚Üí remove import from index.js if deleted

    logo.svg ‚Üí remove any import from App.js

So the error ‚Äúcannot find index‚Äù happens when either src/index.js or public/index.html is missing.

‚úÖ Rule of thumb: never delete index.js in React; that is essential. Everything else is optional.

