You said:
src/Login.js
  Line 34:11:  The href attribute requires a valid value to be accessible. Provide a valid, navigable address as the href value. If you cannot provide a valid href, but still need the element to resemble a link, use a button and change it with appropriate styles.
i am getting this warning
ChatGPT said:

Ah! That warning comes from React‚Äôs accessibility rules (eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y).

Your code has:

<a href="#" onClick={handleForgotPassword}>Forgot Password?</a>

    href="#" is not a valid navigable URL, so React complains.

    Using an <a> tag like this can cause unexpected page jumps or accessibility issues.

Fix 1: Use a <button> instead

This is the recommended approach if the link triggers a function:

<button 
  type="button" 
  className="forgot-password-link" 
  onClick={handleForgotPassword}
>
  Forgot Password?
</button>

Then in your CSS, make it look like a link:

.forgot-password-link {
  background: none;
  border: none;
  color: #ffd6a5;
  text-decoration: underline;
  cursor: pointer;
  font-size: 14px;
  padding: 0;
}

‚úÖ This keeps it accessible and removes the React warning.
Fix 2: Provide a valid href

If you actually have a URL to navigate to (like /forgot-password), you can do:

<a href="/forgot-password">Forgot Password?</a>

    In React Router, you‚Äôd use <Link> instead:

import { Link } from "react-router-dom";

<Link to="/forgot-password">Forgot Password?</Link>

Recommendation

Since your ‚ÄúForgot Password?‚Äù triggers a function (handleForgotPassword), use the <button> approach. It‚Äôs semantically correct and accessible.

If you want, I can rewrite your entire Login.js component with this fix included and ready for React. Do you want me to do that?
