You said:
if i wanna it to do nothing like go to the page login agian for now then i should write?
ChatGPT said:

Exactly! If you want the ‚ÄúForgot Password?‚Äù button or link to do nothing for now (just stay on the same page), you can implement the function to prevent any default action and simply not do anything else.

Here‚Äôs how you can do it:
1. Using a Button (recommended)

const handleForgotPassword = () => {
  // Do nothing for now
};

    Since a <button> doesn‚Äôt have a default navigation like <a> does, you don‚Äôt need preventDefault().

    Clicking it will simply do nothing, and the page will stay as-is.

2. If you were using an <a> (not recommended)

const handleForgotPassword = (e) => {
  e.preventDefault(); // prevents jumping to "#"
  // Do nothing else
};

    e.preventDefault() stops the browser from navigating anywhere.

    But as we fixed earlier, it‚Äôs better to use a <button> for this case.

‚úÖ Summary:

    For now, your forgot password button can just call an empty function:

<button
  type="button"
  className="forgot-password-link"
  onClick={handleForgotPassword}
>
  Forgot Password?
</button>

const handleForgotPassword = () => {
  // intentionally left blank
};

The user will click it, and nothing will happen, which is perfect for a placeholder.

If you want, I can also show a quick way to make the Login button do the same ‚Äúdo nothing for now‚Äù behavior so the whole page is ready to test. Do you want me to do that?
You said:
no i mean uwing <a> instead of #
ChatGPT said:

Ah! Got it ‚Äî you want to use <a> instead of <button> but still have it do nothing for now, without React complaining about an invalid href.

Here‚Äôs the clean way to do it:
Option 1: Use javascript:void(0) as href

<a href="javascript:void(0)" onClick={handleForgotPassword}>
  Forgot Password?
</a>

    javascript:void(0) is a valid href, so React won‚Äôt warn.

    Clicking the link does nothing.

Option 2: Use a valid page URL temporarily

If you want it to reload the login page (stay on the same page), you can set the href to the current path:

<a href="/login" onClick={handleForgotPassword}>
  Forgot Password?
</a>

    Clicking it will reload /login.

    You can later replace it with the real forgot password page.

‚úÖ Recommendation

    For a placeholder that does nothing, javascript:void(0) is the simplest.

    If you later implement routing, you can switch it to a proper path or React Router <Link>.

So your final snippet would look like:

<a href="javascript:void(0)" onClick={handleForgotPassword}>
  Forgot Password?
</a>

and in JS:

const handleForgotPassword = () => {
  // do nothing for now
};

This satisfies React‚Äôs accessibility rules and avoids warnings.

