You said:
i do not want routing
ChatGPT said:

Ah! got it ‚Äî you want separate pages for Login and Sign Up but without using React Router or routing. In that case, the simplest approach is to use separate HTML files or conditionally render components manually.

Here‚Äôs how you can handle it without routing:
Option 1: Separate HTML Pages

    Keep index.html as usual.

    Create login.html and signup.html inside public/ folder.

    Each HTML file includes a <div id="root"></div> and loads the React app.

    In Login.js, use a regular <a href="/signup.html">Sign Up</a> link to go to the Sign Up page.

Example in Login.js:

<div className="footer-text">
  <p>
    Don't have an account? <a href="/signup.html" className="toggle-link">Sign Up</a>
  </p>
</div>

Example in SignUp.js:

<div className="footer-text">
  <p>
    Already have an account? <a href="/login.html" className="toggle-link">Login</a>
  </p>
</div>

    No React Router required.

    Clicking the link reloads the page but it‚Äôs a simple approach for small projects.

Option 2: Conditional Rendering in App.js (No URL change)

If you don‚Äôt want page reloads but also don‚Äôt want routing, you can toggle between Login and Sign Up components inside App.js:

// src/App.js
import React, { useState } from "react";
import Login from "./Login";
import SignUp from "./SignUp";

function App() {
  const [showSignUp, setShowSignUp] = useState(false);

  return (
    <div className="App">
      {showSignUp ? (
        <SignUp onSwitch={() => setShowSignUp(false)} />
      ) : (
        <Login onSwitch={() => setShowSignUp(true)} />
      )}
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;

Login.js (modified for toggle callback)

const Login = ({ onSwitch }) => {
  const handleLogin = () => {};
  return (
    <div className="login-container">
      {/* login form */}
      <div className="footer-text">
        <p>
          Don't have an account?{" "}
          <span className="toggle-link" onClick={onSwitch}>
            Sign Up
          </span>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

SignUp.js (modified for toggle callback)

const SignUp = ({ onSwitch }) => {
  const handleSignUp = () => {};
  return (
    <div className="signup-container">
      {/* signup form */}
      <div className="footer-text">
        <p>
          Already have an account?{" "}
          <span className="toggle-link" onClick={onSwitch}>
            Login
          </span>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

    No URL change occurs.

    User clicks toggle ‚Üí React re-renders the other component.

    Still keeps Login and SignUp separate components.

‚úÖ Summary

    Option 1: Use separate HTML pages ‚Üí links reload the page ‚Üí simplest, no React Router.

    Option 2: Keep React components separate ‚Üí use a toggle in App.js ‚Üí no routing, no reload, better UX.

I can write a complete ready-to-use version of Option 1 or 2 for your project with Login and Sign Up pages if you want.

