so is it possible to add books  component even nothing will be clicked to get it like login in home page 
ChatGPT said:

Yes! Absolutely ‚Äî you can show the Books component immediately on the Home page, independent of whether Login or Sign Up is clicked. The forms can appear conditionally on top, but the Books component can always render below them.

Here‚Äôs how it works:
Example HomePage.js

import React, { useState } from "react";
import Login from "./Login";
import SignUp from "./SignUp";
import Books from "./Books";
import "./HomePage.css";

const HomePage = () => {
  const [showLogin, setShowLogin] = useState(false);
  const [showSignUp, setShowSignUp] = useState(false);

  return (
    <div className="homepage-wrapper">
      {/* Buttons to open forms */}
      <div className="top-buttons">
        <button onClick={() => { setShowLogin(true); setShowSignUp(false); }}>
          Login
        </button>
        <button onClick={() => { setShowSignUp(true); setShowLogin(false); }}>
          Sign Up
        </button>
      </div>

      {/* Forms appear only if state is true */}
      <div className="forms-container">
        {showLogin && <Login />}
        {showSignUp && <SignUp />}
      </div>

      {/* Books component always visible */}
      <div className="books-container">
        <Books />
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default HomePage;

‚úÖ Behavior

    Books component is always rendered ‚Äî visible even if no button is clicked.

    Login/Sign Up forms only show if the user clicks their respective buttons.

    You can style .books-container to take as much space as needed.

Optional UX idea

    If you want the Login/Sign Up forms always visible on top, just render them without conditional state:

<div className="forms-container">
  <Login />
  <SignUp />
</div>

    Then Books will always appear below.

    This mimics a typical library homepage: forms on top, content below.

If you want, I can make a final HomePage layout with Login and Sign Up side by side on top and Books below, fully ready to copy-paste.

