where should this be put we that is json
ChatGPT said:

Great question ‚Äî this JSON does NOT go inside your React code directly.

This is the format your backend should return when React calls your fetchAllBooks() function.

Let me explain clearly:
‚úÖ Where This JSON Should Be?
‚úî In your backend database ‚Üí backend API ‚Üí returned as JSON

Your React Books component expects the backend to send an array like:

[
  {
    "id": 1,
    "isbn": "978-3-16-148410-0",
    "title": "Book Title",
    "genre": "Fiction",
    "year": 2020,
    "authors": "Author Name",
    "publisher": "Publisher Name",
    "pages": 320,
    "available": true
  },
  {
    "id": 2,
    "isbn": "978-1-61-729413-6",
    "title": "Clean Code",
    "genre": "Programming",
    "year": 2008,
    "authors": "Robert C. Martin",
    "publisher": "Prentice Hall",
    "pages": 464,
    "available": false
  }
]

Your backend returns this when React does:

const res = await fetch("/api/books");
const data = await res.json();
setBooks(data);

‚ùå Where this JSON SHOULD NOT be

    Not inside your React components

    Not inside Books.js

    Not inside BookCard.js

    Not inside the frontend at all

üü© Correct Backend Flow (Example)
1. Database Table (books)

Stores:

id | isbn | title | genre | year | authors | publisher | pages | available

2. Backend Route

Example in Node.js:

app.get("/api/books", (req, res) => {
  const books = [
    {
      id: 1,
      isbn: "978-3-16-148410-0",
      title: "Book Title",
      genre: "Fiction",
      year: 2020,
      authors: "Author Name",
      publisher: "Publisher Name",
      pages: 320,
      available: true
    }
  ];

  res.json(books);
});

Or in Spring Boot:

@GetMapping("/api/books")
public List<Book> getAllBooks() {
    return bookService.getAllBooks();
}

3. React fetches that JSON

Books.js:

const fetchAllBooks = async () => {
  const res = await fetch("/api/books");
  const data = await res.json();
  setBooks(data);
};

üü¶ If You Want Dummy Data Before Backend Is Ready

You can temporarily put this inside Books.js:

setBooks([
  {
    id: 1,
    isbn: "978-3-16-148410-0",
    title: "Book Title",
    genre: "Fiction",
    year: 2020,
    authors: "Author Name",
    publisher: "Publisher Name",
    pages: 320,
    available: true
  }
]);

But this is only for testing until backend works.
‚≠ê Summary

üìå The JSON format I showed you is backend output format
üìå React reads it using fetch() and then displays it
üìå You should NOT hardcode JSON inside React components
üìå You CAN temporarily use dummy data while backend is not ready
