You said:
ok now i want you to take data from web and put it in books variable to test only with same attributes
ChatGPT said:

Good idea. For testing, you can pull real data from a public API like Gutendex (free) to fill your books state temporarily. Gutendex doesn‚Äôt give all the exact fields you want (e.g. publisher, number of copies), but you can map its response to your structure partially (and mock up missing fields).

Here‚Äôs an example of how to fetch from Gutendex, map the data to your books state, and set some dummy values for the fields that the API doesn‚Äôt provide.
Example: Using Gutendex to Populate books State for Testing

In Books.js, modify your fetchAllBooks like this:

// src/components/Books/Books.js
import React, { useEffect, useState } from "react";
import BookCard from "./BookCard";
import BookDetails from "./BookDetails";
import "./Books.css";

const Books = () => {
  const [books, setBooks] = useState([]);
  const [selectedBook, setSelectedBook] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetchAllBooks();
  }, []);

  const fetchAllBooks = async () => {
    try {
      const res = await fetch("https://gutendex.com/books");
      const data = await res.json();
      // data.results is an array of books
      const mapped = data.results.map((b) => {
        return {
          id: b.id,
          isbn: b.id + "", // Gutendex doesn't provide ISBN, so mock it
          title: b.title,
          genre: b.bookshelves && b.bookshelves.length > 0 
                   ? b.bookshelves[0] 
                   : "Unknown",
          year: b.download_count, // not real year, just for testing
          authors: b.authors.map((a) => a.name).join(", "),
          publisher: "Unknown Publisher", // mock
          pages: b.format ? 0 : 0, // Gutendex doesn‚Äôt provide page count, so mock
          copies: Math.floor(Math.random() * 10), // mock number of copies
        };
      });
      setBooks(mapped);
    } catch (err) {
      console.error("Failed to fetch books", err);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div className="books-wrapper">
      <h2 className="books-title">Library Books</h2>

      <div className="books-grid">
        {books.length === 0 ? (
          <p>Loading books...</p>
        ) : (
          books.map((book) => (
            <BookCard
              key={book.id}
              book={book}
              onClick={() => setSelectedBook(book)}
            />
          ))
        )}
      </div>

      {selectedBook && (
        <BookDetails book={selectedBook} onClose={() => setSelectedBook(null)} />
      )}
    </div>
  );
};

export default Books;

What This Code Does

    Calls the free Gutendex API: https://gutendex.com/books
    Free API Hub

    Maps the response to your book object shape, filling in missing fields with mock/dummy values.

    copies is randomly generated for testing.

    Sets the mapped data into books state so your BookCard and BookDetails components can render correctly.

If you want more realistic data (with publisher, ISBN, etc.), you could also use Open Library API:

    Search API: https://openlibrary.org/search.json?q=the+hobbit
    Open Library

    Or get edition details via: /api/books?bibkeys=ISBN:...&format=json
    Open Library+2Open Library+2

If you like, I can write a fetch function using Open Library API that gives almost all the fields you defined (ISBN, title, authors, publisher, etc.). Do you want me to do that?
You said:
 <p>No books available.</p>
why first time you made it like this and second one
   <p>Loading books...</p>
when cheking length
ChatGPT said:

Great observation ‚Äî let me explain why the first version showed ‚ÄúNo books available.‚Äù and the second version shows ‚ÄúLoading books‚Ä¶‚Äù, and what the correct behavior should be.
‚úÖ Why Version 1 showed:

<p>No books available.</p>

Because in the first version we assumed:

    Books will load instantly

    An empty array means ‚Äúyour backend returned nothing‚Äù

But this causes a problem:
When the component first loads, books = [], so React immediately shows ‚ÄúNo books available‚Äù before the fetch even runs.

That looks wrong ‚Äî the user sees ‚ÄúNo books‚Äù even though the data is just loading.
üü© Why Version 2 uses:

<p>Loading books...</p>

Because version 2 uses the empty state as a loading indicator, which is a more natural approach when you first fetch data from the backend.

    Before fetch completes ‚Üí books.length === 0 ‚Üí show "Loading..."

    After fetch:

        If books exist ‚Üí show book cards

        If backend returns nothing ‚Üí show "No books available"

‚≠ê The BEST solution (correct and clean)

We should track loading separately rather than relying on books.length:
‚úÖ Correct Final Version

Use a loading state:
Books.js

const [books, setBooks] = useState([]);
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

useEffect(() => {
  fetchAllBooks();
}, []);

const fetchAllBooks = async () => {
  try {
    const res = await fetch("https://gutendex.com/books");
    const data = await res.json();

    // map the data ...
    const mappedBooks = data.results.map(/* mapping code */);

    setBooks(mappedBooks);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error("Error fetching books:", err);
  } finally {
    setLoading(false);
  }
};

Then in your JSX:

{loading ? (
  <p>Loading books...</p>
) : books.length === 0 ? (
  <p>No books available.</p>
) : (
  books.map((book) => (
    <BookCard key={book.id} book={book} onClick={() => setSelectedBook(book)} />
  ))
)}

üí° Explanation
‚úî When the page opens

loading = true ‚Üí show ‚ÄúLoading books‚Ä¶‚Äù
‚úî When fetch finishes

    loading = false

    If books returned ‚Üí show books

    If backend returned an empty array ‚Üí ‚ÄúNo books available‚Äù

This avoids confusion.
üéâ Summary
Situation	What Should Display
Fetching books	Loading books...
Fetch returned empty list	No books available.
Fetch returned data	Book grid

If you want, I can give you the clean full updated Books.js file including the loading state, the fetch, and the mapped API data.
