            onChange={(e) => setPassword(e.target.value)}
it was not here
ChatGPT said:

Ah! That explains the confusion. In the original version I gave you before, the input fields were just uncontrolled, meaning they didn‚Äôt use React state:

<input type="text" id="username" placeholder="Enter username" />
<input type="password" id="password" placeholder="Enter password" />

    No value or onChange ‚Äî React doesn‚Äôt track what the user types.

    That‚Äôs fine if you only want a static form and handle the values later (e.g., reading via document.getElementById), but it‚Äôs not the ‚ÄúReact way.‚Äù

Why I added onChange and useState

    To make the inputs controlled components ‚Äî React state stores their current values.

    This lets you easily read the entered username/password in handleLogin():

const handleLogin = () => {
  console.log(username, password);
  onLogin(); // simulate login
};

If you want it exactly like your original version:

<div className="input-group">
  <label htmlFor="username">Username</label>
  <input type="text" id="username" placeholder="Enter username" />
</div>

<div className="input-group">
  <label htmlFor="password">Password</label>
  <input type="password" id="password" placeholder="Enter password" />
</div>

    No useState required.

    handleLogin will have to manually read the values from the DOM if you need them:

const handleLogin = () => {
  const username = document.getElementById("username").value;
  const password = document.getElementById("password").value;
  console.log(username, password);
  onLogin(); // simulate login
};

‚úÖ Summary
Version	Pros	Cons
Uncontrolled (no onChange)	Simple, exactly like original	Harder to use React features, need DOM queries
Controlled (with onChange & useState)	React tracks values, easier to handle forms	Slightly more code, differs from original HTML-like version

