Perfect! Now we‚Äôre talking about a more standard layout with navigation and routing. To achieve this in React, we should use React Router, which allows us to have separate pages for Login, SignUp, and Profile while keeping Books visible on the homepage.

Here‚Äôs a full solution:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Install React Router

npm install react-router-dom

2Ô∏è‚É£ App.js (with routes)

// src/App.js
import React from "react";
import { BrowserRouter as Router, Routes, Route } from "react-router-dom";
import HomePage from "./components/HomePage/HomePage";
import Login from "./components/Login/Login";
import SignUp from "./components/SignUp/SignUp";
import Profile from "./components/Profile/Profile";

function App() {
  return (
    <Router>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/" element={<HomePage />} />
        <Route path="/login" element={<Login />} />
        <Route path="/signup" element={<SignUp />} />
        <Route path="/profile" element={<Profile />} />
      </Routes>
    </Router>
  );
}

export default App;

3Ô∏è‚É£ HomePage.js (Books + buttons layout)

// src/components/HomePage/HomePage.js
import React from "react";
import { Link } from "react-router-dom";
import Books from "../Books/Books";
import "./HomePage.css";

const HomePage = () => {
  return (
    <div className="homepage-wrapper">

      {/* TOP BUTTONS */}
      <header className="homepage-header">
        <div className="left-buttons">
          <Link to="/profile">
            <button>Profile</button>
          </Link>
        </div>
        <div className="right-buttons">
          <Link to="/login">
            <button>Login</button>
          </Link>
          <Link to="/signup">
            <button>Sign Up</button>
          </Link>
        </div>
      </header>

      {/* BOOKS SECTION */}
      <main className="homepage-main">
        <Books />
      </main>

    </div>
  );
};

export default HomePage;

4Ô∏è‚É£ HomePage.css (layout)

.homepage-wrapper {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  min-height: 100vh;
  background-color: #f3e9dc;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
}

/* HEADER */
.homepage-header {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
  padding: 15px 30px;
  background-color: #8b5e3c;
}

/* BUTTON GROUPS */
.left-buttons,
.right-buttons {
  display: flex;
  gap: 15px;
}

.homepage-header button {
  padding: 10px 20px;
  background-color: #d4a373;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 5px;
  font-weight: bold;
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: 0.3s;
}

.homepage-header button:hover {
  background-color: #c08c5a;
  color: white;
}

/* BOOKS SECTION */
.homepage-main {
  flex: 1;
  padding: 20px;
}

‚úÖ How it works

    Profile button on the left, Login/SignUp buttons on the right.

    Clicking any button navigates to its own page using React Router (/login, /signup, /profile).

    Homepage (/) still shows Books under the header.

    Each page (Login, SignUp, Profile) can have its own layout without cluttering the homepage.

If you want, I can also show a clean Login page and SignUp page layout for these routes so that when the user clicks the button, they see the form nicely centered like a normal website.

